VALUES
(1, 30, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'And Zilpah Leah’s maid bare Jacob a son.', 0, 40, 'connection', 'Sibling Rivalry Theme', 'The narrative of Zilpah bearing Jacob a son echoes themes found in Genesis 16:1-4, where Sarah gives Hagar to Abraham in a similar attempt to build a family. Both instances highlight the complexities of familial relationships and the tension between wives and concubines. Such connections underscore how human attempts to fulfill divine promises can lead to conflict and strife within families.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 16:1-4", "description": "The story of Sarah and Hagar, illustrating similar dynamics."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'bare Jacob a son', 23, 39, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty in Family', 'This passage reflects the theological theme of God''s sovereignty over lineage and family. Many scholars believe that despite the human strategies employed, God''s purpose prevails in the establishment of the Israelite tribes. The birth of Gad and Asher through Zilpah signifies God''s active role in fulfilling His covenant promises to Jacob, demonstrating that God''s will can be accomplished through unexpected means.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Insights on God''s providence in family matters."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'Zilpah Leah’s maid', 4, 22, 'question', 'Role of Servants', 'What does Zilpah’s role as a maid reveal about the societal values of the time, and how does it challenge or affirm our understanding of worth and identity in God’s eyes today? This prompts reflection on how God can use those in seemingly lowly positions to fulfill His purposes.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'A troop cometh:', 15, 30, 'connection', 'Military Connotation', 'The phrase ''A troop cometh'' reflects a military context, reminiscent of Numbers 1:3 where the numbering of Israel’s warriors is described. This connection emphasizes Leah''s perception of her son''s birth as a significant victory or addition to her family, likening her situation to that of a military campaign. It reveals the cultural importance of sons in ancient Israel, often viewed as warriors and protectors.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Numbers 1:3", "description": "Describes the numbering of Israel''s warriors."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'and she called his name Gad.', 31, 59, 'theology', 'Significance of Names', 'In biblical times, names held deep significance, often reflecting one''s destiny or character. Leah naming her son Gad, which means ''fortune'' or ''luck'' in Hebrew, suggests a theological viewpoint that recognizes God''s providence in granting her a son amid her struggles. Many scholars believe this indicates Leah''s understanding of her role in God''s unfolding plan for Israel, where each tribe would have a distinct purpose.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of names in the biblical context."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'A troop cometh:', 15, 30, 'question', 'Understanding Victory', 'What does it mean for Leah to declare ''A troop cometh'' upon the birth of Gad? How might this perspective of victory influence our understanding of challenges in our own lives? Reflecting on this can lead to deeper insights about how we view our struggles and victories as part of God''s greater narrative.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'And Zilpah Leah’s maid bare Jacob a second son.', 0, 47, 'connection', 'Sibling Dynamics', 'This verse highlights the complex family dynamics in Jacob''s household, paralleling the themes of sibling rivalry and competition found in Genesis 25:21-26, where Esau and Jacob contend for their father''s blessing. The challenges faced by Jacob’s family illustrate the broader theme of God''s providence working through imperfect human relationships.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 25:21-26", "description": "Esau and Jacob''s rivalry serves as a precursor to the tensions in Jacob''s own family."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'bare Jacob a second son', 23, 46, 'theology', 'Divine Purpose in Family', 'Many scholars believe this moment signifies God''s overarching plan, as He uses the births of these sons to fulfill His covenant with Jacob. The subsequent generations will become the tribes of Israel, illustrating how God works through human actions and decisions to achieve divine purposes, despite the struggles within families.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Henry discusses how the births of Jacob''s sons contribute to God''s plan for Israel."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'And Zilpah Leah’s maid', 0, 22, 'question', 'Role of Maidservants', 'What does the inclusion of Zilpah, Leah''s maid, reveal about the value of individuals in God''s plan? How can we see God''s purpose at work through those who might be overlooked or marginalized in society?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'a second son', 34, 46, 'greek', 'Significance of ''Second''', 'שֵׁנִי (sheni, H8145) - second, another. The Hebrew term emphasizes not just the sequential order of the son born but also the idea of continuation and multiplication of lineage, which is significant in the context of God’s promise to Abraham regarding his descendants.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8145", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term emphasizing the importance of birth order."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'Happy am I, for the daughters will call me blessed', 15, 65, 'connection', 'Joy in God''s Favor', 'Leah’s declaration of happiness parallels the beatitudes found in Matthew 5:3-12, where Jesus speaks about the blessedness of those who are humble and reliant on God. This connection emphasizes the theme of divine favor and the joy that comes from being recognized by others as blessed, which resonates with the idea of God''s approval in the lives of His people.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 5:5", "description": "Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'and she called his name Asher', 67, 96, 'theology', 'Significance of Names', 'In biblical times, names carried significant meaning and often reflected one''s character or destiny. The name Asher, meaning ''happy'' or ''blessed'', suggests that Leah perceives her son as a source of joy and fulfillment. Many scholars believe this highlights a theological principle that God’s blessings can transform one’s identity and circumstances, reinforcing the importance of recognizing and celebrating God’s gifts.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of names in biblical narratives."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'Happy am I, for the daughters will call me blessed', 15, 65, 'question', 'Seeking Validation', 'What does Leah’s desire for the daughters to call her blessed reveal about the human need for validation and recognition? In what ways do we seek affirmation from others, and how does understanding our identity in Christ reshape this need?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'and she called his name Asher', 67, 96, 'greek', 'Understanding Asher', 'אשר (Asher, H836) - happy, blessed. This Hebrew word encapsulates Leah''s emotional state and the joy she associates with her son. It emphasizes the significance of happiness not just as a feeling but as a state of being rooted in divine blessing.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H836", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for Asher."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'mandrakes in the field', 56, 78, 'connection', 'Mandrakes in Scripture', 'Mandrakes are mentioned in other ancient texts and are often associated with fertility. For example, in Song of Solomon 7:13, mandrakes are linked to love and desire. This connection enhances our understanding of Rachel''s desperation for children and the cultural significance of mandrakes in fertility rituals. The mention of mandrakes in Genesis 30 highlights the intense rivalry and emotional struggles between Rachel and Leah.', 'arrow.triangle.branch', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Song of Solomon 7:13", "description": "Mandrakes are mentioned in a poetic context, emphasizing their association with desire and fertility."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'Give me, I pray thee, of thy son’s mandrakes.', 145, 190, 'question', 'Desire for Control', 'What does Rachel''s request for mandrakes reveal about her understanding of motherhood and the lengths she is willing to go to gain control over her situation? This moment prompts reflection on how we pursue what we desire, even at the expense of relationships. How does this tension reflect our own struggles with envy and desire?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'And Reuben went in the days of wheat harvest', 0, 44, 'theology', 'Significance of Harvest', 'The timing ''in the days of wheat harvest'' carries theological implications, as harvest time is often associated with God''s provision and abundance. This period can symbolize the blessings that come from God, underscoring the contrast with the personal strife between Rachel and Leah. Many scholars believe that this setting highlights the tension between divine providence and human desire.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 30:14", "description": "Commentaries often discuss the theological implications of agricultural metaphors in Genesis."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'found mandrakes in the field', 50, 78, 'greek', 'Mandrake Meaning', 'Although this passage is in Hebrew, the concept of mandrakes has been discussed in various translations. The Hebrew term for mandrake is דּוּדָאִים (dudaim, H1725), which is often associated with love and desire. Understanding the cultural and historical context of mandrakes can deepen our appreciation of the emotional dynamics at play in this story.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1725", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for mandrakes."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'Is it a small matter that thou hast taken my husband?', 23, 76, 'theology', 'Jealousy and Rivalry', 'This passage highlights the intense rivalry between Leah and Rachel, representing broader themes of jealousy and the human condition. Many scholars believe this reflects the struggles within families and the complexities of love and loyalty. Such dynamics can lead to discord and strife, reminding readers of the importance of reconciliation and understanding in relationships.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 29:31-35", "description": "Explores the familial tensions and emotions between Leah and Rachel."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'and wouldest thou take away my son’s mandrakes also?', 77, 129, 'connection', 'Mandrakes in Scripture', 'The mention of mandrakes (H178) connects to other instances in Scripture where mandrakes symbolize fertility and desire. In Song of Solomon 7:13, mandrakes are linked to love and desire, emphasizing their cultural significance. This connection illustrates Rachel''s desperation for children and Leah''s struggle for recognition, deepening the understanding of their motivations.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Song of Solomon 7:13", "description": "Discusses the symbolic use of mandrakes in love and desire."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'And Rachel said, Therefore he shall lie with thee to night for thy son’s mandrakes.', 130, 213, 'question', 'Value of Relationships', 'What does this negotiation reveal about the value placed on relationships versus physical needs? How does this mindset shape our understanding of commitment and sacrifice in our own lives? Reflecting on this situation encourages a deeper examination of how we prioritize our connections with others.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'and wouldest thou take away my son’s mandrakes also?', 77, 129, 'greek', 'Mandrake Meaning', 'מַנְדְּרָה (mandrâh, H178) - mandrake, a plant believed to have fertility-enhancing properties. This term''s use in this context highlights the desperation for fertility and the lengths to which Rachel and Leah are willing to go to secure their positions within the family.', 'textformat.abc', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'Thou must come in unto me; for surely I have hired thee with my son’s mandrakes.', 89, 169, 'connection', 'Mandrakes in Scripture', 'The mention of mandrakes in this passage connects to the broader biblical theme of fertility and divine providence. In Song of Solomon 7:13, mandrakes are associated with love and fertility. This suggests that Rachel''s desire for mandrakes indicates a deeper yearning for children, paralleling Leah''s desperation. Both women are ultimately seeking God''s blessings through means that reveal their cultural context of childbearing.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Song of Solomon 7:13", "description": "Mandrakes are linked to love and desire in the poetic imagery of the Song."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'for surely I have hired thee with my son’s mandrakes.', 116, 169, 'theology', 'Value of Relationships', 'This passage illustrates the transactional nature of relationships in ancient cultures, where children and fertility were highly valued commodities. Many scholars believe this reflects a broader theological understanding of human relationships, where love and intimacy are often overshadowed by societal pressures and expectations. It raises questions about how we value relationships today, challenging us to consider the motivations behind our connections.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'And Jacob came out of the field in the evening,', 0, 47, 'question', 'Jacob''s Role as Provider', 'Why is Jacob''s return from the field emphasized in this verse? What does it reveal about his responsibilities as a husband and provider? Reflecting on this can lead to a deeper understanding of the balance between work and family life, and how we fulfill our duties in relationships.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'And he lay with her that night.', 170, 201, 'greek', 'Hebrew Word for ''Lay''', 'שָׁכַב (shakab, H7901) - to lie down, to rest, to have sexual relations. This term underscores the intimacy of the act, indicating a deeper connection beyond mere obligation. It highlights the interplay between desire and duty in the context of marital relationships, reinforcing the complexities of love in this narrative.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7901", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'And God hearkened unto Leah', 0, 27, 'connection', 'God''s Attention to Prayer', 'This phrase echoes the sentiment found in 1 Samuel 1:20, where Hannah''s prayer is heard by God, leading to the birth of Samuel. Both women experience God''s responsiveness to their deep desires for children, highlighting a theme of divine favor and intervention in matters of personal longing. Leah''s situation also reflects God''s awareness of human struggles, reminding us that He is attentive to our cries for help.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Samuel 1:20", "description": "Hannah''s prayer and God answering her"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'and she conceived', 29, 46, 'theology', 'Divine Blessing of Conception', 'This passage suggests the theological understanding that children are a blessing from God, a theme prevalent throughout Scripture. Many scholars believe that conception is not merely a biological process but a divinely orchestrated event, reflecting God''s sovereignty over life. This view aligns with Psalm 127:3, asserting that ''children are a heritage from the Lord,'' emphasizing the sacred nature of procreation.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 127:3", "description": "Children as a heritage from God"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'bare Jacob the fifth son', 52, 76, 'question', 'Understanding Leah''s Family Dynamics', 'What does the birth of Jacob''s fifth son reveal about Leah''s relationship with Jacob and her status within the family? As Leah continues to bear children while Rachel struggles with infertility, how does this affect the dynamics of their rivalry? This invites reflection on how God uses family relationships to fulfill His purposes and the lessons we can learn about acceptance and value in our own relationships.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'God hath given me my hire', 15, 40, 'connection', 'Divine Provision Theme', 'This phrase connects to Genesis 29:32, where Leah acknowledges God''s action in her life by bearing children. It emphasizes a recurring biblical theme: God''s provision in response to human actions and desires. Leah''s understanding of her ''hire'' reflects a belief in God''s direct involvement in her fertility struggles, which parallels with Hannah''s prayer in 1 Samuel 1:27, where she attributes her child to God''s answered prayers.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 29:32", "description": "Leah acknowledges God''s role in her fertility."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Samuel 1:27", "description": "Hannah credits God for granting her a child."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'because I have given my maiden to my husband', 42, 86, 'theology', 'Cultural Context of Marriage', 'Many scholars believe this passage highlights the cultural practices surrounding marriage in ancient Israel, particularly the use of concubines. Leah''s action of giving her maid to Jacob reflects the norms of the time, where women sought to secure their status and favor through childbearing. This reflects broader theological themes of family dynamics and God''s sovereignty over human customs.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the cultural context of Leah''s actions."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'and she called his name Issachar', 88, 120, 'question', 'Meaning of Names', 'What significance does naming carry in this context, specifically with ''Issachar''? How does understanding the meaning of Issachar, which is often interpreted as ''There is a reward,'' influence our understanding of God''s blessings in our lives? Reflecting on how names reflect identity and purpose can deepen our insight into God''s plans for us.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'And Leah conceived again, and bare Jacob the sixth son.', 0, 55, 'connection', 'Leah''s Fertility and God''s Plan', 'This verse echoes the themes of divine intervention and the fulfillment of God''s promises seen in Genesis 29:31, where God opened Leah''s womb because she was unloved. The continuation of Leah''s fertility highlights God''s favor towards her and serves to fulfill His covenant promise to multiply Jacob''s descendants. This connection underscores the importance of lineage in the narrative of God''s people.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 29:31", "description": "God''s blessing upon Leah''s fertility"}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 35:23-26", "description": "The significance of Jacob''s sons in Israel''s lineage"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'And Leah conceived again, and bare Jacob the sixth son.', 0, 55, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty in Childbearing', 'Many scholars believe this passage illustrates God''s sovereignty over human circumstances, particularly in the realm of family and procreation. Leah''s ability to conceive, despite her social status and personal struggles, indicates that God''s plans are fulfilled through unexpected means. This reflects the broader theological theme of God''s providence, where He orchestrates events for His purposes, even in the midst of human conflict and rivalry.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discussion on God''s providence in the lives of the patriarchs"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'And Leah conceived again, and bare Jacob the sixth son.', 0, 55, 'question', 'The Meaning of Multiplicity', 'What significance does the birth of the sixth son hold in your understanding of God''s covenant with Jacob? How might this experience of Leah inform our understanding of God''s grace in our own lives, particularly when we feel overlooked or undervalued?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'God hath endued me with a good dowry;', 15, 52, 'theology', 'Divine Blessing and Dowry', 'Leah''s acknowledgment of God endowing her with a ''good dowry'' reflects the biblical theme of divine providence and blessing. Many scholars believe this expresses Leah''s understanding that her children are gifts from God, enhancing her status and security in her marital relationship. This illustrates the theological principle that God''s blessings often manifest in tangible ways, reinforcing one''s position within family and society.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'now will my husband dwell with me,', 53, 87, 'question', 'Marital Relationships', 'What does Leah''s hope for her husband''s dwelling with her reveal about the dynamics of marital relationships in the ancient context? How does this desire for closeness and stability resonate with our modern understanding of marital bonds?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'because I have born him six sons:', 88, 121, 'connection', 'Significance of Sons', 'The importance of male offspring in biblical culture is underscored in this verse. This can be cross-referenced with Genesis 49:3-4, where Jacob blesses his sons and acknowledges their roles within Israel. This connection highlights the societal value placed on sons as heirs and leaders, shaping the family legacy and tribe''s future.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 49:3-4", "description": "Jacob''s blessings of his sons and their significance."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'and she called his name Zebulun.', 122, 154, 'greek', 'Zebulun''s Meaning', 'זְבוּלֻן (Zebulun, H2074) - dwelling, honor. The name signifies Leah’s hope that her husband will ''dwell'' with her, reflecting a deeper longing for recognition and stability in their relationship. Zebulun is later associated with the tribe that plays a significant role in the history of Israel, reinforcing the idea that names carry prophetic significance.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2074", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term Zebulun, indicating its meaning."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'And afterwards she bare a daughter, and called her name Dinah.', 0, 62, 'connection', 'Connection to Family Dynamics', 'The mention of Dinah’s birth connects to Genesis 34, where her story unfolds, highlighting the challenges and consequences of family relationships. This serves to show the complexity of Leah''s family life, as well as the larger narrative of Jacob''s lineage, emphasizing the importance of all family members in God''s plan.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 34:1", "description": "Dinah''s story continues here, showing the implications of her identity."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'called her name Dinah.', 40, 62, 'theology', 'Significance of Names', 'In biblical tradition, names often carry deep significance, reflecting character or destiny. The name Dinah, which means ''judged'' or ''vindicated'', suggests a divine purpose and foreshadows the trials she will face. Many scholars believe this emphasizes God''s justice within family dynamics and the unfolding of His plan through individual lives.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of names in biblical texts."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'bare a daughter', 19, 34, 'question', 'Role of Women in Scripture', 'What does the phrase ''bare a daughter'' reveal about the value of women in the biblical narrative? Considering the cultural context of Leah, how might this shape our understanding of women''s roles and their contributions in God''s plan?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'afterwards', 4, 14, 'greek', 'Hebrew Term Analysis', 'אַחַר (achar, H310) - afterwards, behind. This term signifies a chronological sequence that not only marks time but also suggests progression in Leah''s story. It reflects the unfolding of God''s plan in a specific order, emphasizing the importance of each event in the narrative.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H310", "description": "Strong''s number for deeper study of the term."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'And God remembered Rachel,', 0, 26, 'connection', 'Divine Remembrance Theme', 'The phrase ''God remembered Rachel'' echoes Genesis 8:1, where God remembers Noah during the flood. This connection highlights God''s faithfulness and timing in delivering His people from distress. Both instances illustrate that divine remembrance leads to action, signifying God''s ongoing relationship with humanity.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 8:1", "description": "God remembers Noah and the creatures in the ark, showing His care and intervention."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'and God hearkened to her,', 27, 52, 'theology', 'God''s Listening Nature', 'This passage suggests that God is attentive to the cries of His people. Many scholars believe that God''s willingness to ''hearken'' reflects His covenantal love and commitment to respond to the needs of His followers, reinforcing the biblical theme that God is a responsive and compassionate deity.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'and opened her womb.', 53, 73, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Opened''', 'פָּעַר (pa''ar, H6491) - to open, to release. This Hebrew term signifies not just a physical opening but also a spiritual release of blessings. Rachel''s womb being ''opened'' symbolizes God''s direct intervention in her life, transforming her barrenness into fruitfulness, highlighting the importance of God''s timing in His promises.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6491", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word used here."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'God remembered Rachel,', 4, 26, 'question', 'Reflecting on Divine Memory', 'What does it mean for God to ''remember'' someone? How does understanding this divine action influence your view of God’s involvement in your personal struggles and prayers?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'God hath taken away my reproach:', 45, 77, 'connection', 'Reproach in Scripture', 'This concept of ''reproach'' is echoed in other biblical texts, such as Isaiah 54:4, where God assures His people that they will no longer be ashamed or reproached. Rachel''s declaration signifies not just her personal struggle but also a broader theme of God''s redemptive work in lifting shame. The connection emphasizes God''s faithfulness in addressing the deep-seated feelings of inadequacy and societal judgment faced by women in ancient contexts.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Isaiah 54:4", "description": "God promises to remove shame from His people."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And she conceived,', 0, 18, 'greek', 'Conception and Life', 'The Hebrew word for ''conceived'' here is הָרָה (harah, H2030) - to conceive, to be pregnant. This term emphasizes the miraculous nature of childbirth, especially in the context of Rachel''s initial barrenness. It highlights God''s intervention in her life, illustrating a theme of divine grace that transforms a situation of despair into one of hope and fulfillment.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2030", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term related to conception."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 30, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'God hath taken away my reproach:', 45, 77, 'theology', 'God''s Role in Reproach', 'This verse suggests that God actively removes shame and reproach from His people. Many scholars believe this reflects a broader theological principle that God is concerned with the dignity and honor of individuals, especially those marginalized or suffering. The act of God removing reproach can be seen as a precursor to the New Testament understanding of redemption and restoration through Christ, who addresses both spiritual and social shame.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses God''s concern for dignity and honor in His people."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');